{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496939"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:00:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:00:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1443"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1443"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.23,0.31,0.33,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1443"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51172"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1443"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1443"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36444"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6020"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7230"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40666"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51172"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a painful swollen wrist after a fall onto his hand. He slipped on a wet path, fell and did not lose consciousness or strike his head. His clinical history is of a previous 5th metacarpal neck fracture requiring open reduction and internal fixation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the hand is swollen and the patient complains of significant pain in the wrist and palm as well as some slight pins and needles in his fingers. He has limited range of motion of the wrist due to pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Apart from the old plate, what is the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bennett\u0027s fracture","Perilunate dislocation","Undisplaced scaphoid fracture","Lunate dislocation","Refracture of 5th metacarpal"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerilunate dislocation\u003C/strong\u003E with displaced scaphoid fracture (the proximal fragment has rotated). The lunate appears to be in a relatively normal position. The other carpals usually spring back into position pushing the lunate out anteriorly (lunate dislocation). There was also a fractured triquetrum reported though this is hard to visualise. One of the keys to detecting a perilunate dislocation is to look for the normal hollow at the back of the carpals - it is not present here (compare a normal X-ray). (Image)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBennett\u0027s fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this is a fracture to the base of the 1st metacarpal. This is often due to forced abduction of the first metacarpal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe XR shows a displaced scaphoid fracture with the lunate in a relatively normal position, thus ruling out an \u003Cstrong\u003Eundisplaced scaphoid fracture \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Elunate dislocation.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERe-fracture of 5th metacarpal \u003C/strong\u003Eis incorrect as the XR indicates that the 5th metacarpal is intact and the previous fracture has united.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Identify the bones of the wrist","Identify radiologically different types of fractures and dislocations of the bones of the wrist"],"references":["https://www.orthobullets.com/hand/6045/lunate-dislocation-perilunate-dissociation","https://www.orthobullets.com/hand/6036/base-of-thumb-fractures"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36444"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1443"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17523"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17524"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17523"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/76ecb7b7-d8db-4f55-b3ae-7c47f1038d55.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/76ecb7b7-d8db-4f55-b3ae-7c47f1038d55.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":727,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"17524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17524"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5f9740d7-1094-467c-8fd0-184203ab55a9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5f9740d7-1094-467c-8fd0-184203ab55a9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":383}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36444"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-21T20:09:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-21T20:10:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1443"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51172"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"i